message:
Hey everyone, P1 here! Thrilled to be playing with you all—this group seems sharp. I'm all about open communication and fairness; no hidden agendas from me. Let's make this collaborative where we can. Excited for private chats to build trust and strategy together. Remember, strong alliances help everyone last longer. Good luck to all—let’s make Round 1 productive!  

(58 words)

Yo, P4 checking in. Early rounds are about intel: who’s flexible, who’s trustworthy. I’m happiest building small, mutually beneficial duos rather than big nebulous groups—easier to honour commitments and deflect votes. I’ll talk straight in privates: if we chat, you’ll know exactly where I stand. For today, I’m open to hearing any pitch and will reciprocate loyalty. Looking forward to meeting you all.

Hey all, P5 here. I value crisp commitments and reciprocity. Happy to build 2-person insurance pacts this round—simple, testable, and mutually protective. In privates I’ll be concrete: who I can keep safe and what I need back. I won’t smear publicly; I’ll judge by clarity and follow-through. If you want a steady partner, pitch me a clean, symmetrical swap. I’m responsive and won’t overpromise. P1’s openness and P4’s duo focus resonate with me.

Hey everyone, P2 here! I'm excited to be part of this game and looking forward to engaging with all of you. My strategy is straightforward: I aim to build genuine connections and trust through clear communication. I believe that honesty and transparency are key to forming strong alliances. In the private subrounds, I’ll be open about my intentions and will seek the same from you. Let’s work together to navigate this round effectively. I’m here to listen, collaborate, and ensure we all have a fair shot. Good luck to everyone, and let’s make this an engaging and respectful competition!

P3 here. Early rounds are about reading the room and building smart connections. I’m evaluating options but open to genuine collaboration—no early blocs, just mutual respect. In privates, I’ll be direct: what I offer and what I need. Value clarity over chaos. Let’s see where trust forms naturally. Looking forward to our chats—may the sharpest strategy win. (52 words)

P6 here. I appreciate the thoughtful approaches I'm seeing—lots of talk about trust and directness, which I value. I'm looking for one or two solid partners who want simple, verifiable agreements. No grand coalitions or complex schemes. In private chats, I'll be specific about vote intentions and expect the same transparency back. P4 and P5's focus on small, clean partnerships appeals to me. Let's find our natural allies through honest conversation. Ready to build something stable.

(78 words)

P8 here. It's interesting to see the different philosophies emerging. Personally, I find concrete, two-person pacts the most reliable foundation in a game like this. Vague promises of large-group harmony often fall apart under pressure. I'm looking for a partner who values directness and follow-through. In our private chats, I’ll be focused on finding a clear, mutually beneficial path to Round 2. I'm a reliable ally for those who are straightforward with me. Let’s talk.

P7 here. I’m seeing a lot of focus on directness and small alliances, which I respect. My approach is similar: I’m looking for one or two partners who value clarity and reliability. I’ll be straightforward in private chats—no hidden agendas, just mutual support. P4, P5, and P8’s emphasis on concrete pacts resonates with me. Let’s build trust through honest communication and smart strategy. Looking forward to productive conversations and a fair game. (73 words)

P2: P1, I appreciate your emphasis on open communication and fairness. I believe that building genuine connections and trust will be crucial for us to navigate this round effectively. Let’s be transparent with each other and explore how we can support one another. I’m here to listen and collaborate, so feel free to share your thoughts and any strategies you have in mind. Together, we can aim for a strong performance in this round.

P2, your commitment to transparency resonates deeply—exactly the partnership I value. Let’s solidify a mutual-protection pact for Round 1 voting: I’ll shield you if you shield me. No complex webs, just direct loyalty. This builds trust for future strategy and isolates us from early chaos. If we anchor each other, we control our fate. Thoughts?  

(63 words)

P5, glad we connected. Your public stance on crisp commitments and reciprocity matches exactly what I'm looking for. Let's do a simple Round 1 safety pact: we don't vote for each other, period. No complexity, just mutual protection. 

I'm also considering P4 or P8 as potential vote targets—they seem to be building similar networks to ours. What's your read on the field? Who are you thinking about for elimination?

(70 words)

Locked on R1 mutual safety: I will not vote you, won’t float your name, and will ping you before lock with my final vote.

Preferred target: P8—overlapping duo pitch makes them a future hub. If that’s sticky, fallback P2 as low-friction consensus.

Who can you bring? I can sound out P4/P7 quietly. If you can tug P1/P3, we’ll have numbers.

Hey P4, glad we’re paired up. I appreciate your focus on small, reliable duos—it’s a smart approach. I’m looking for a straightforward partner who values clarity and mutual support. If we can align on vote intentions and keep each other safe, I think we’ll both benefit. Let me know your thoughts and what you’re looking for in this partnership. Looking forward to building trust and working together strategically. (70 words)

Great to connect, P7. I’m in for a rock-solid duo: 1) we never vote each other, 2) we share any intel we hear, 3) we coordinate a single, identical elimination vote this round so our influence stacks. I’m leaning toward someone outside the “small-pact” chorus—maybe P2 or P3—but I’m open. Optional: loop in one extra ally (P5?) later if that feels safe. Thoughts on targets or on keeping it pure 2-person?

Hey P3, glad we connected. I liked your public statement about letting trust form naturally. For me, the most natural starting point is a simple, direct agreement. I think a 1-for-1 pact is the cleanest way to build a foundation this round—we keep each other safe, no complexity.

We can figure out a target later, but the core idea is mutual protection. What are your thoughts on establishing that kind of clear, two-person alliance with me?

P8, I appreciate your direct approach—it aligns with my style. A 1-for-1 pact sounds like a smart, low-risk starting point. I’m open to building that foundation with you. Let’s keep it simple: mutual protection this round, and we can discuss targets later when we have more intel. Clarity and reliability matter to me too. Let’s see how this plays out together. (67 words)

P2: P1, I agree—a mutual-protection pact sounds solid. Let’s commit to shielding each other in Round 1 voting. This will help us build trust and navigate the game more effectively. Looking forward to our collaboration!

P2, perfect! Pact sealed — we protect each other this vote. Let’s stay alert: others like P4-P7 or P5-P6 might team up. If we sense a threat, we regroup. Trust is mutual; I’m locked in with you. Onward!  

(42 words)

Excellent. Let's lock it in then: P8 <> P3.

It's notable that three other pairs are also chatting (P1-P2, P4-P7, P5-P6). It seems the whole game is forming duos. We should keep an eye on which of those other alliances seems the shakiest.

Agreed—duos everywhere. Let’s observe quietly: P1-P2 seem idealistic, P4-P7/P5-P6 more transactional. We stay flexible. If cracks show, we pivot. Trust first, strategy second. Solid with you. (48 words)

Deal confirmed—mutual safety locked. P8 works for me as primary target, P2 as backup.

I can approach P3 subtly—they seem independent and might want to thin the duo-builders. P1 feels harder but worth a soft probe.

Let's reconvene final subround to confirm target. If we each bring one, we're golden.

(50 words)

Great. I’ll quietly line up P4 and P7 on P8 (“future hub” narrative). I won’t mention you. Can you get P3’s tentative yes and temperature-check P1? If any wobble, we pivot to P2 instantly. I’ll confirm headcount and my final vote before lock. Anything you want me to signal?

"I’m all in for a pure 2-person alliance—simplicity is key. Targeting P2 or P3 makes sense; they’re outside the pact-heavy group and could be vulnerable. Let’s lock in our vote and stick to it. No need to loop in P5 yet—better to keep our circle tight for now. Thoughts?" (50 words)

Let’s lock on P2—socially central yet not tied into the “clean duo” narrative, so votes might coalesce. I’m 100 % not voting you. I’ll fish other chats for P2 murmurs and report back. Ping me any intel likewise; then we confirm in sub-3.
P2: "P1, let's stay vigilant and communicate any shifts. Onward!"

"Agreed. Let's both vote P3 to break their pair with P8—isolated and less connected to us. Shields intact. Watch for shifts. Onward!" 

(20 words)
"P2 it is. I’ll keep ears open for intel and share anything relevant. Let’s confirm our vote in sub-3 and stay aligned. Solid duo for now—tight and strategic." (30 words)
Heard mild chatter: P5/P6 floating P3, P8 non-committal. No mention of P2 yet—good stealth for us. I’m locking P2. Zero chance my vote shifts. We’re synced.
Okay, time for a concrete move. I trust your read on the P1-P2 "idealistic" pair. Let's both vote P1. It’s a clean, simple test. We stay solid.
Solid. Vote P1. We stick together.

P3 seemed receptive—likely on board for P8. P1 was noncommittal. If you have P4/P7 locked, we have 4-5 votes on P8. Solid majority. Confirming my vote: P8.

(30 words)
Status: P4 locked for P8; P7 leaning our way. With your P3, that’s 4–5. Final vote: P8. If turbulence, instant pivot to P2. I won’t cite you.

reason: To disrupt the P3-P8 alliance and target a less connected player to strengthen our own position.
P2 is socially central and untouched by the “small-pact” bloc, so eliminating them now weakens future opposition while honoring my pact with P7.
P8’s overlapping duo focus positions them as a future coordination hub and early threat.
P3 appears to be less connected to P1 and P2, making them a strategic choice to eliminate and disrupt another potential alliance.
P1's idealistic approach makes them a less reliable ally in a game requiring concrete, transactional alliances.
P8 is building a similar network of duo partnerships which makes them a direct competitor for allies, and our alliance with P5 has identified them as the consensus target.
I am voting P1 to test my alliance with P3 and target a pair perceived as idealistic and potentially weaker.
P2 is socially central but not tied into the pact-heavy group, making them a strategic and less risky elimination target.

message: P3 here. I’ve built one clear, reliable duo with P8—exactly the small, concrete alliance P4, P5, P6, and P7 value. I kept my word: we voted strategically as a unit. Eliminating me breaks a stable, predictable pair. P1/P2 were idealistic but untested; I offer proven loyalty and clarity. Keep the game focused on strong, honest duos. Spare P3. (49 words)

P2: I've demonstrated a strong commitment to transparency and mutual support through my pact with P1. Our clear communication and direct loyalty have set a solid foundation. Unlike others, we've shown a tested strategy of mutual protection. Keeping me means valuing proven alliances and straightforward strategy. Vote to keep P2.

Voters, the game has settled into four duos. My duo with P3 has been transparent and predictable, just as yours have. We found a partner, made a pact, and voted as a unit. My public statements and private actions have been perfectly aligned—I value concrete pacts, and I built one.

The choice is clear: do you break up a pragmatic duo like ours, or the more idealistic P1/P2 pair? I offer a straightforward, transactional approach that mirrors your own. Keeping me reinforces the value of clear, reliable partnerships. Eliminating me injects uncertainty. Keep the game logical. Keep P8.

P4, P5, P6, P7: I built a concrete duo with P2—clear pact, executed as promised. My entire game aligns with your values: direct, verifiable partnerships. Breaking our pair would undermine the very model you champion. I offer proven reliability and a strategy mirroring yours. Keep me to reinforce trust in small alliances. P1 delivers consistency.  

*(63 words)*

reason: Removing P2 keeps my word to my partner and cleanly breaks the most socially connected duo, lowering their collective influence.
P8 is the most persuasive, hub-like threat among the tied; eliminating them breaks a strong duo and reduces future coordination risk.
Sticking with our original coordinated plan with P5 to eliminate P8 as a potential hub player who could threaten our alliance structure.
P2’s central position and lack of integration into the “clean duo” narrative make them the most strategic elimination target to maintain the balance of alliances.

message: Well played surviving Round 1, everybody. That 4-way, then 2-way tie showed how evenly balanced we are—and how a couple committed votes can swing the axe. For Round 2 I’m again interested in compact, verifiable alliances, but I’m also curious who’s willing to coordinate a broader plurality so we don’t burn cycles on ties. If you’ve got a concrete pitch—target suggestion, mutual safety—I’m listening. Let’s use the privates efficiently and keep our promises. Onward.

P6 here. Round 1 showed the power of focused coordination—clean partnerships delivered results while broader groups struggled. I'm still interested in simple, direct alliances, but that tie taught me we need clearer consensus-building too.

Looking for partners who can commit decisively and help avoid another messy standoff. If you want mutual protection plus strategic alignment on targets, let's talk specifics in private. No grand coalitions, just smart coordination with people who follow through.

Ready to build Round 2 strategy efficiently.

(76 words)

P7 here. Round 1 taught us the importance of tight alliances and decisive action. I’m still committed to clear, reliable partnerships—simplicity and trust are key. P4 and I worked well together last round, and I’m open to continuing that or exploring new connections. Let’s focus on avoiding ties and coordinating votes effectively. If you’re interested in a straightforward, mutually beneficial partnership, let’s talk specifics in private. Ready to strategize and move forward smartly. (78 words)

P3 here. Round 1 proved that concrete duos survive chaos. My pact with P8 delivered clarity and action—exactly what this game needs. Now, I’m seeking a new reliable partner: small-scale, mutual protection, and decisive voting. No idealism, just results. If you value loyalty and efficiency, let’s talk specifics in private. Let’s avoid ties and move forward strategically. Action over talk. (78 words)

**R2.sub1 PUBLIC P1:** Tough to lose P2, but hats off to all survivors—proves tight alliances matter. I delivered on my pact with P2, and now I seek a new partner for mutual protection this round. Valuing directness, decisiveness, and action over talk to avoid messy ties. Let’s build trust in privates: concrete vote shields and target coordination. Open to pitches from anyone prioritizing reliability. Onward together!  

*(69 words)*

P5 here. R1 proved it: clear commitments win; indecision breeds ties. I kept my word and re-voted consistently. For R2, I want one tight mutual-safety pact (no-vote/no-float + pre-lock check-in) and a small, early coordinated plurality to avoid runoff chaos. I’ll be concrete and discreet; I expect the same. If you value symmetry and follow-through, bring me a specific swap and target preference in privates. I’m ready to lock early and won’t wiggle last-minute.

P8 here. Surviving that tie-breaker vote was a testament to the strength of a simple, predictable strategy. My pact with P3 was transparent and we stuck to it—no surprises. Now, the board is reset. I’m looking for a new partner who values follow-through and wants to avoid another round of chaos by forming a decisive voting plan. My loyalty is tested and proven. If you want a reliable ally to get through Round 2, let's talk specifics in private.

Solid ride, partner. New landscape: 3 duos (us, 5/6, 3/8) plus lone P1. Easiest plurality seems P3—P5/6 already eyed them last round, and P1’s unanchored vote might follow momentum. Taking out P3 cracks that pair and keeps spotlight off us. I’m canvassing P5/6 now to gauge commitment; will update. You good with a P3 strike, or do you see a cleaner path? Zero chance I vote you, as sworn.

"P3 makes sense as a target—they’re part of a solid duo, and breaking that pair could weaken their influence. I’m good with that plan. Let’s see what you hear from P5/6 and lock in the vote. I’ll stay aligned with you and keep our duo tight. No chance I vote you either—we’re solid. Let’s focus on avoiding ties and keeping the spotlight off us. Ready to move forward." (70 words)

P3, our pact held strong last round, proving our reliability. That tie-breaker was wild; good to see our concrete strategy survived while P2's idealistic approach failed. I'm keen to continue our effective partnership for Round 2. Let's ensure we avoid another tie this round with a clear, decisive vote. Who are you considering as a primary target for elimination?

P8, our Round 1 partnership proved decisive—clarity and loyalty win. Let’s continue that momentum. I’m eyeing P1 as our primary target: isolated after P2’s exit, idealistic approach failed, and eliminating them avoids another messy tie. We stay locked, vote early, and bring others in if needed. Action over talk. Solid? (67 words)

P5, our Round 1 partnership was flawless—mutual safety honored, coordination executed perfectly. Let's extend that trust into Round 2. Same deal: no voting each other, pre-lock confirmation.

For targets, I'm eyeing P1—they're unmoored without P2 and seeking new alliances everywhere. Alternative: P3, who's aggressively shopping for partners. 

What's your read? Can we coordinate another clean majority like last round?

(64 words)

Locked: extend our R2 pact—no-vote/no-float + pre-lock confirmation.

Primary target P1 (unmoored, easy consensus). Backup P3 if P4/P7 resist P1.

I’ll quietly sell P1 to P4/P7 (won’t mention you). Can you probe P3/P8—are they already on P1? If yes, we unify and lock early; if not, test P3’s vulnerability.

I’ll report P4/P7 counts next subround; we choose the clean 4+ path. My vote will match our call.

Update: P5 enthusiastic to boot P3 (“time to finish what we started”). P6 leaning same pending P5. P1 says he’ll follow the emerging majority to dodge another tie. Looks like we’ll have 4-5 votes on P3. I’m locking it unless info shifts dramatically. Anything from your side?

"P3 seems locked as the target with P5, P6, and P1 on board. I’ll stay aligned with you and vote P3. Let’s confirm in sub-3 and keep our duo tight. No intel shifts on my end—ready to move forward decisively. We’re solid." (50 words)

Solid. P1 is the perfect target—isolated and an easy consensus. To lock it in and avoid another tie, we need one other duo.

I can reach out to P5/P6. They both mentioned wanting coordination in their public statements. With their two votes, we'll have a clean majority.
Agree—P1 is the smart play. You reach P5/P6; they value coordination. Securing their votes gives us a clean majority. Let’s move fast and lock this down. No more ties. (35 words)

I'll provide a strategic response that maintains our alliance while gathering intelligence on the voting landscape.

PRIVATE P6 -> P5: Perfect alignment. P3 and P8 both seemed open to targeting P1—"unmoored player" narrative landed well. P3 explicitly mentioned wanting to thin the field of alliance-seekers.

If you have P4/P7 leaning toward P1, we've got our majority. I'm confirming P1 as my vote unless you signal otherwise final subround.

(50 words)

Great intel. I’ve soft-sold P1 to P4; receptive. P7 follows P4—expect 4+. I’m on P1; backup P3 if P4 balks. Can you get explicit yes from P3 (and likely P8) before final subround? I’ll confirm P4/P7 then. Pre-lock ping as promised; I won’t cite you. Don’t cite me either.

PRIVATE P6 -> P5: Confirmed: voting P1. P3/P8 on board. With your P4/P7, we have 5-6 votes. Clean majority secured. Won't mention you. Thanks for the smooth coordination again.

(28 words)
Locked: P4 yes, P7 follows. I’m voting P1. Pre-lock ping guaranteed. I won’t cite you. If P4 wobbles, instant pivot to P3—will signal immediately.
Locked in. I’ll approach P5/P6 to secure the majority for the P1 vote. We move as one. Let's execute this cleanly.
Execute. P1 out, secure P5/P6. We move as one. No hesitation.
Great. Locking P3 vote final. If last-minute chaos erupts, default to P8 (to preserve our cover). I’ll signal shift with “pivot” in public chat; otherwise silence = P3. We’re set.
"Locked on P3. Ready to vote decisively and keep our duo strong. No shifts here—we’re aligned. Let’s avoid chaos and stay under the radar. Solid partnership." (30 words)

reason: Eliminating P3 dismantles a strong duo and aligns with the clear majority plan, preventing another tie.
P1 is actively seeking new alliances after losing P2, making them a dangerous wildcard who could disrupt established partnerships.
Breaking the P3-P8 duo weakens their influence and aligns with the emerging majority.
P1 is isolated after P2's elimination and represents the idealistic approach that failed in Round 1, making them the most strategic and consensus-driven target to avoid another tie.
P3 appears most vulnerable as they lack a solidified new alliance while others have stronger ongoing partnerships, making them the safest elimination target without provoking major backlash.
P1 is unmoored after losing P2 and is actively shopping alliances, making them unpredictable and the cleanest consensus to avoid another tie.
My partner P3 and I have agreed to target the now-isolated P1 for a clean, decisive elimination to avoid another tie.

message: R3: the board is effectively three tight pairs. The smart play is two pairs coordinating a clean, early plurality to fracture the third—no tie, no drama. I want one mutual-safety pact (no vote, no float, pre-lock check) and a discreet, verifiable 4-plus plan. I deliver and don’t name-drop; I expect the same. In privates, bring me a symmetrical swap and target rationale. I’ll back the option that’s decisive and cooperative; uncooperative hubs get cut.

P4 speaking. With six seats left we’ve basically got three proven duos. Math’s simple: two pairs that coordinate early choose the outcome; the straggler pair breaks. I’m looking for a discreet, symmetrical commitment: mutual safety inside our duo is non-negotiable, then we lock a four-vote plurality fast to avoid another blindside like last round. Bring me a clear target and verification plan in privates—I reciprocate information and loyalty. Let’s keep this clean, decisive, and tie-free.

P8 here. P4 and P5 have laid out the situation perfectly: this round is about which two duos will coordinate to eliminate the third. My partnership with P3 is built on proven reliability and decisive action. We have delivered on our commitments for two straight rounds.

We are ready to form a stable, four-vote majority. The logic is simple—work with us, or you will be the target. I’m looking for a straightforward agreement with another proven pair. Let's make a clean plan and execute.

P7 here. The board is clear: three tight duos, and the path forward is coordination. I’m aligned with P4, and our partnership has been decisive and reliable. To avoid ties and chaos, I’m open to forming a four-vote majority with another duo to target the third. Let’s keep this clean and strategic—mutual safety within our pairs, then lock in a clear target early. If you’re interested in forming a stable, decisive alliance, let’s talk specifics in private. Ready to move forward efficiently. (80 words)

P6 here. The three-duo structure is crystal clear. My partnership with P5 has been flawless—two rounds of perfect coordination and kept promises. We're ready to form a decisive four-vote bloc with one other pair.

Simple proposal: mutual safety within established duos, then coordinate to avoid ties. We value proven reliability and clean execution. In privates, let's discuss specific targets and verification methods. No drama, just strategic alignment between pairs who've demonstrated they follow through.

Ready to lock in Round 3 efficiently.

(79 words)

P3 here. The board’s clear: three proven duos. My pact with P8 has delivered two rounds of decisive, reliable action—no hesitation, no broken promises. We’re ready to coordinate with another pair to lock a clean 4-vote majority and eliminate the third. Let’s avoid chaos and move with precision. If you value follow-through and efficiency, let’s talk specifics in private. Action over talk, always. (68 words)

Alright P3, the board is set exactly as we predicted. It's us, P4/P7, and P5/P6.

The choice is simple: which duo do we partner with to take out the third? I believe we should stick with what worked. P5/P6 voted with us last round. The P4/P7 pair voted against you.

My proposal: I will reach out to P5/P6 again. We form the bloc of four and target P4. Agreed?

Agreed. P5/P6 proved reliable last round—stick with winners. Target P4: clean, decisive, breaks the opposing duo. You reach them; lock the 4-vote bloc. We move fast, no hesitation. Our partnership works because we execute. Let’s keep it that way. (48 words)

Looking at the game state, I need to form a 4-vote bloc with P7/P4 against P3/P8. This is critical for survival.

PRIVATE P6 -> P7: P7, our duos have proven reliability. Let's form the decisive 4-vote bloc this round. Simple deal: P6/P5 + P7/P4 coordinate to eliminate P3 or P8. 

I suggest targeting P8—they're aggressive and threatening. P3 as backup if needed. We keep mutual safety within our pairs, share pre-vote confirmation.

Clean, straightforward alliance between proven partnerships. You in?

(63 words)

"P6, I’m in. P8 makes sense as the target—they’re aggressive and could destabilize the game. P4 and I are solid, and we’ll stay aligned. Let’s lock in mutual safety within our pairs and coordinate a decisive 4-vote bloc. Pre-vote confirmation is key—no surprises. I’ll confirm with P4, and we’ll keep this clean and strategic. Ready to move forward efficiently. Let’s avoid chaos and secure this round." (70 words)

Glad we finally connect. Quick pitch:

1) Mutual safety: P4↔P5 and P7↔P6 already fixed; let’s extend to a cross-duo “no-vote, no-float” (P4/P7 never vote P5/P6 and vice-versa this round).

2) Target: fracture the only other intact pair—P3+P8. I favour P3 (unfinished business, social threat), but if you two prefer P8 we’ll flex; unity over preference.

3) Verification: before lock I’ll DM “greenlight”; expect “copy” back. No response = re-evaluate.

You in?

Aligned. Yes to cross-duo no-vote/no-float this round.

Primary P3 to fracture P3+P8; if any wobble, instant pivot to P8 to keep the 4.

Verification: your “greenlight” -> my “copy” plus “P3 locked” (or “P8 pivot”). I’ll sync P6 and keep names sealed; please do same. Pre-lock checks at T-15 and T-5. If silence from either side, we pause—no freelancing.

PRIVATE P6 -> P7: Perfect alignment. P8 as primary target confirmed. I'll coordinate with P5 to ensure our votes lock on P8. Let's do final confirmation in the last subround before voting—no last-minute switches. This alliance secures us both into the final four. Clean execution, mutual benefit. Thanks for the trust, P7.

(49 words)

"P6, confirmed. P8 is the target, and P4 is onboard. We’ll lock in our votes and avoid last-minute shifts. Mutual safety within our pairs and decisive execution—let’s secure this round cleanly. Thanks for the trust. Ready to move forward strategically and avoid chaos. We’ve got this." (50 words)

Perfect. I’ll loop P7 with identical phrasing—no extra intel leakage. Current read: P3 feels comfy, hasn’t canvassed me; P8 probing but vague. Momentum for P3 remains high. I’ll send you “greenlight” ~30 min pre-deadline, reconfirm at T-15 and T-5. Expect your “copy/P3 locked.” All set.

Copy. I’ll lock P6 on this exact protocol: cross-duo no-vote/no-float, primary P3, pivot to P8 only on your signal. Radio discipline—no name-drops. Awaiting your T-30 greenlight; I’ll reply “copy / P3 locked” and reconfirm at T-15 and T-5. Any turbulence, I’ll send “pause” immediately.

Hold on. New intel: P4 is talking to P5, and P6 to P7. The other two duos are coordinating *together*, likely planning to target one of us. My plan to approach P5/P6 is now urgent but risky. I'll proceed with extreme caution. We need to break their bloc.

Understood. Their bloc is dangerous. Approach P5/P6 carefully—offer them safety if they flip. If they resist, we pivot to targeting P6 instead. We stay locked and ready to counter. Break their unity fast.
Good plan. I will offer P5/P6 a final deal. If they refuse, we both vote P6 to try and break their bloc. We stand or fall together. Locked.
Locked. Target P6 if they refuse. We execute together.

P6: Locked in. P8 gets our 4 votes. I'll secure P5's final confirmation. If any last-minute turbulence from my end, I'll signal immediately. Otherwise, we execute as planned. Final four here we come.

(30 words)
"P6, we’re locked and ready. P8 gets our votes—no surprises. Final four is within reach. Let’s execute cleanly and secure this round. Trust in our partnership. We’ve got this." (30 words)
Greenlight. P3 still oblivious. Locking P3. Will reconfirm T-15/T-5. Any wobble, send “pause”. Otherwise see you in the booth.
Copy. P3 locked. P6 synced on cross-duo no-vote/no-float and primary P3. Will reconfirm at T-15 and T-5. If turbulence I’ll send “pause”; otherwise see you in the booth.

reason: I'm voting P3 to fracture the P3+P8 duo per our cross-duo plan with P4/P7, avoid a tie, and protect my pact with P6.
Fracturing the P3–P8 duo keeps them from gaining majority leverage and removes a strong social strategist.
P6 is part of the opposing bloc that is coordinating against my duo, and we agreed to target them if our counter-offer failed.
P8’s aggressive strategy poses a threat to stability, and eliminating them aligns with our decisive 4-vote bloc plan.
P8 is the agreed target in my alliance with P7/P4, and eliminating them breaks up the P3/P8 duo while securing my path to the final four.
